{"cursor":"12352","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Sentience' is the ability to feel, perceive, or be conscious, or to experience\nsubjectivity. Eighteenth century philosophers used the concept to distinguish\nthe ability to think (\"reason\") from the ability to feel (\"sentience\"). In\nmodern western philosophy, sentience is the ability to experience sensations\n(known by the technical term \"qualia\"). For Eastern philosophy, sentience is a\nmetaphysical quality of all things that requires respect and care. The concept\nis central to the philosophy of animal rights, because sentience is necessary\nfor the ability to suffer, which is held to entail certain rights.\n","linknr":431,"url":"Sentience","recorded":1362373661,"links":32,"instances":["animal_rights","psychology","buddhism","philosopher","robot"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Animal rights","Consciousness studies","Personhood","Philosophy of mind","Self","Subjective experience"],"headings":["Philosophy and sentience","Indian religions","Animal rights and sentience","Artificial intelligence","Science fiction","Sentience quotient","See also","References","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Japanese_Macaque_Fuscata_Image_370_%28cropped%29.jpg/90px-Japanese_Macaque_Fuscata_Image_370_%28cropped%29.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/33/Dogs_nose.jpg/90px-Dogs_nose.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/2pigs_%28cropped%29.jpg/90px-2pigs_%28cropped%29.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Bottlenose_Dolphin_KSC04pd0178_%28cropped%29.jpg/90px-Bottlenose_Dolphin_KSC04pd0178_%28cropped%29.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Loxodonta_africana_in_Tsavo_East_National_Park_%28edited%29.jpg/90px-Loxodonta_africana_in_Tsavo_East_National_Park_%28edited%29.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Orpington_chicken_head_%28cropped%29.jpg/90px-Orpington_chicken_he